03626nam a2200529Ia 9780774855082DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a9780774855082  a(DE-B1597)661950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aN6545.D39 2006eb 7aART0150402bisacsh04a7091 aDawn, Leslie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNational Visions, National Blindness :bCanadian Art and Identities in the 1920s /cLeslie Dawn. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (456 p.) :b26 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early decades of the twentieth century, Canada sought to define itself as an independent dominion with allegiance to the British Empire. The visual arts were considered central to the formation of a distinct national identity, and the Group of Seven's landscapes became part of a larger program to unify the nation and assert its uniqueness. National Visions, National Blindness traces the development of this program and illuminates its conflicted history. Using newly discovered archival evidence, Leslie Dawn revises common interpretations of several well-known events and rescues others from obscurity. He problematizes conventional perceptions of the Group as a national school and underscores the contradictions inherent in international exhibitions showing unpeopled landscapes alongside Northwest Coast Native arts and the "Indian" paintings of Langdon Kihn and Emily Carr. Dawn examines how this dichotomy forced a re-evaluation of the place of First Nations in both Canadian art and nationalism. National Visions, National Blindness is an elegantly written work offering new and insightful analysis, and will be of great interest to readers and researchers of Canadian art history, First Nations art and history, tourism, cultural politics, museum studies, and ethnographic practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArt, Canadiany20th century. 0aIndians in art. 0aLandscapes in art. 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855082423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855082/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles